    <abstract>
      <title>Abstract</title>
      <sec id="abs1">
        <title>Background</title>
        <p>DNA methylation plays a key role in the regulation of gene expression and carcinogenesis. Bisulfite sequencing studies mainly focus on calling single nucleotide polymorphism, different methylation region, and find allele-specific DNA methylation. Until now, only a few software tools have focused on virus integration using bisulfite sequencing data.</p>
      </sec>
      <sec id="abs2">
        <title>Findings</title>
        <p>We have developed a new and easy-to-use software tool, named BS-virus-finder (BSVF, <ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://scicrunch.org/resolver/RRID:SCR_015727">RRID:SCR_015727</ext-link>), to detect viral integration breakpoints in whole human genomes. The tool is hosted at <ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://github.com/BGI-SZ/BSVF">https://github.com/BGI-SZ/BSVF</ext-link>.</p>
      </sec>
      <sec id="abs3">
        <title>Conclusions</title>
        <p>BS-virus-finder demonstrates high sensitivity and specificity. It is useful in epigenetic studies and to reveal the relationship between viral integration and DNA methylation. BS-virus-finder is the first software tool to detect virus integration loci by using bisulfite sequencing data.</p>
      </sec>
    </abstract>
